*-----------------------------------
* Overrides of MILL.LIB's TIME HOURS/MINUTES/SECONDS attributes.
* Same numeric formatting (INTEGER/DECIMAL, LEFT_PLACES, RIGHT_PLACES,
* CANNOT_BE_DECIMAL) as the master library - only the hardcoded label
* text (WORD_ADDRESS_BEF/AFT) is removed, so these output bare numbers
* that FrankenOKO_GrblHal_Metric.SRC assembles into its own sentence.
:ATTRNAME=TIME HOURS
:ATTRTYPE=POST
:ATTRVTYPE=INTEGER
:ATTREMARK=Time in Hours, clean display (no inherited MILL.LIB label text)
:CODETYPE=FORMAT
:WORD_ADDRESS_BEF=
:WORD_ADDRESS_AFT=
:LEFT_PLACES=3
:RIGHT_PLACES=0
:CANNOT_BE_DECIMAL
:CANNOT_BE_LEADING
:CANNOT_BE_TRAILING
:CANNOT_BE_SIGNED
:UNITFLAG=NON_CONVERT
:ATTREND
*-----------------------------------
:ATTRNAME=TIME MINUTES
:ATTRTYPE=POST
:ATTRVTYPE=INTEGER
:ATTREMARK=Time in Minutes, clean display
:CODETYPE=FORMAT
:WORD_ADDRESS_BEF=
:WORD_ADDRESS_AFT=
:LEFT_PLACES=3
:RIGHT_PLACES=0
:CANNOT_BE_DECIMAL
:CANNOT_BE_LEADING
:CANNOT_BE_TRAILING
:CANNOT_BE_SIGNED
:UNITFLAG=NON_CONVERT
:ATTREND
*-----------------------------------
:ATTRNAME=TIME SECONDS
:ATTRTYPE=POST
:ATTRVTYPE=DECIMAL
:ATTREMARK=Time in Seconds, clean display
:CODETYPE=FORMAT
:WORD_ADDRESS_BEF=
:WORD_ADDRESS_AFT=
:LEFT_PLACES=2
:RIGHT_PLACES=0
:CANNOT_BE_DECIMAL
:CANNOT_BE_LEADING
:CANNOT_BE_TRAILING
:CANNOT_BE_SIGNED
:UNITFLAG=NON_CONVERT
:ATTREND
*-----------------------------------
* New attributes for the custom OUTPUT_TOOL_LIST table (fixed-width columns).
* Raw storage for per-tool scratch variables, declared first since the
* DISP attributes below reference them via :VAR= (forward references to
* an as-yet-undeclared attribute caused "var not found" compile errors).










































































































* Custom tool-table attributes. Scratch variables declared FIRST since the
* DISP attributes below reference them via :VAR= (forward-reference to an
* undeclared attribute caused "var not found" compile errors previously).
:ATTRNAME=CUR DIAM
:ATTRTYPE=POST
:ATTRVTYPE=DECIMAL
:ATTREMARK=Current tool diameter, mm (loop scratch var)
:ATTREND
*-----------------------------------
:ATTRNAME=CUR TYPE
:ATTRTYPE=POST
:ATTRVTYPE=INTEGER
:ATTREMARK=Current tool type code (loop scratch var)
:ATTREND
*-----------------------------------
:ATTRNAME=CUR COMM
:ATTRTYPE=POST
:ATTRVTYPE=CHARACTER
:ATTRINLEN=30
:ATTREMARK=Current tool description (loop scratch var), ATTRINLEN=30
:ATTREND
*-----------------------------------
* Dedicated arrays for tool Type/Description, written ONLY by our own
* tool-change capture (CALC_BEF_SETON_CODES / CALC_INIT_TOOL_CHANGE_MILL).
* Deliberately NOT named TOOL_TYPE_ARRAY/TOOL_COMM_ARRAY - those native
* array names are also written by MILL.LIB's own CALC_PRELOAD_TOOL
* (fired via GETTOOLS(2,CALC_PRELOAD_TOOL) at the very start of the tape,
* before ARRAY_COUNT is reset to 1 for real tool-change data). That
* leftover preload data was never cleared for the Type/Comment arrays the
* way TOOL_ARRAY(0)/TOOL_DIAM_ARRAY(0) explicitly are, leaving Type/
* Description permanently one tool out of step with Tool#/Diameter.
* Brand-new array names sidestep the collision entirely.
:ATTRNAME=CORR TYPE ARRAY
:ATTRTYPE=POST
:ATTRVTYPE=INTEGER
:ATTRVCNT=100
:ATTREMARK=Corrected tool type array, written only at real tool-change time
:ATTREND
*-----------------------------------
:ATTRNAME=CORR COMM ARRAY
:ATTRTYPE=POST
:ATTRVTYPE=CHARACTER
:ATTRINLEN=80
:ATTRVCNT=100
:ATTREMARK=Corrected tool description array, written only at real tool-change time
:ATTREND
*-----------------------------------
:ATTRNAME=TOOL NUM DISP
:ATTRTYPE=POST
:ATTRVTYPE=INTEGER
:ATTREMARK=Tool Number, zero-padded 3-digit (proven-reliable format)
:CODETYPE=FORMAT
:VAR=TOOL
:LEFT_PLACES=3
:RIGHT_PLACES=0
:CANNOT_BE_DECIMAL
:CANNOT_BE_SIGNED
:UNITFLAG=NON_CONVERT
:ATTREND
*-----------------------------------
:ATTRNAME=TOOL DIAM DISP
:ATTRTYPE=POST
:ATTRVTYPE=DECIMAL
:ATTREMARK=Tool Diameter, zero-padded 3-digit.2-decimal
:CODETYPE=FORMAT
:VAR=CUR_DIAM
:LEFT_PLACES=3
:RIGHT_PLACES=2
:MUST_BE_LEADING
:MUST_BE_TRAILING
:CANNOT_BE_SIGNED
:UNITFLAG=NON_CONVERT
:ATTREND
*-----------------------------------
* LEFT_PLACES=30 experiment: this flag is only ever used for numeric
* decimal-place formatting elsewhere in this library, never on a character
* attribute. Trying it here to see if it forces fixed-width space-padding.
:ATTRNAME=TOOL COMM DISP
:ATTRTYPE=POST
:ATTREMARK=Tool description text for table
:CODETYPE=FORMAT
:VAR=CUR_COMM
:LEFT_PLACES=30
:RIGHT_PLACES=0
:UNITFLAG=NON_CONVERT
:ATTRSPACES=YES
:ATTRUSED=1
:ATTREND
* Custom header-line attributes. Each references the same underlying
* variable as an existing MILL.LIB attribute (S PART NAME, S PROGRAM NUMBER,
* S MACHINE NAME, S CONTROLLER NAME, S MATERIAL, S THICKNESS) via :VAR=, but
* with no baked-in label text, since START_OF_TAPE builds its own custom
* label/layout directly. New attribute names avoid the same override
* collision that broke TIME HOURS/MINUTES/SECONDS earlier in this project.
:ATTRNAME=PART NAME DISP
:ATTRTYPE=POST
:ATTREMARK=Part name, bare value for custom header
:CODETYPE=FORMAT
:VAR=PART NAME
:ATTRINLEN=57
:LEFT_PLACES=0
:RIGHT_PLACES=0
:UNITFLAG=NON_CONVERT
:ATTRSPACES=YES
:ATTRUSED=1
:ATTREND
*-----------------------------------
:ATTRNAME=MACHINE NAME DISP
:ATTRTYPE=POST
:ATTREMARK=Machine name, bare value for custom header
:CODETYPE=FORMAT
:VAR=MACHINE NAME
:ATTRINLEN=54
:LEFT_PLACES=0
:RIGHT_PLACES=0
:UNITFLAG=NON_CONVERT
:ATTRSPACES=YES
:ATTRUSED=1
:ATTREND
*-----------------------------------
* Overriding the ORIGINAL "S MATERIAL" attribute name (not a new parallel
* attribute) - the live CAM-populated value appears linked specifically to
* this exact name. Three prior attempts with a new attribute name all read
* blank despite correct :VAR= values.
* S MATERIAL and S THICKNESS intentionally NOT overridden here - restored
* to pure inheritance from MILL.LIB. New theory tested here: a direct
* calc-level read of the raw material/thickness variables (done early in
* CALC_POST_INITIALIZE, in the .SRC) may resolve differently than going
* through any formatted POST attribute - three prior attempts at the
* attribute level all read blank/zero. MAT_SCRATCH/THICK_SCRATCH below are
* populated by that early calc copy; MATERIAL DISP/THICKNESS DISP read
* those scratch copies for clean display.
* MAT SCRATCH explicitly typed CHARACTER: "6061-T6" was being read as an
* arithmetic expression (6061 minus undefined var T6 = 6061) without this.
:ATTRNAME=MAT SCRATCH
:ATTRTYPE=POST
:ATTRVTYPE=CHARACTER
:ATTRINLEN=53
:ATTREMARK=Copy of material, capped so the full line hits 71 chars max
:ATTREND
*-----------------------------------
:ATTRNAME=THICK SCRATCH
:ATTRTYPE=POST
:ATTRVTYPE=DECIMAL
:ATTREMARK=Copy of thickness, taken via direct calc read early in compile
:ATTREND
*-----------------------------------
:ATTRNAME=MATERIAL DISP
:ATTRTYPE=POST
:ATTREMARK=Material, clean display
:CODETYPE=FORMAT
:VAR=MAT SCRATCH
:LEFT_PLACES=0
:RIGHT_PLACES=0
:UNITFLAG=NON_CONVERT
:ATTRSPACES=YES
:ATTRUSED=1
:ATTREND
*-----------------------------------
:ATTRNAME=THICKNESS DISP
:ATTRTYPE=POST
:ATTRVTYPE=DECIMAL
:ATTREMARK=Thickness, clean display, always 2 decimals
:CODETYPE=FORMAT
:VAR=THICK SCRATCH
:LEFT_PLACES=4
:RIGHT_PLACES=2
:MUST_BE_DECIMAL
:CANNOT_BE_LEADING
:MUST_BE_TRAILING
:CANNOT_BE_SIGNED
:UNITFLAG=NON_CONVERT
:ATTREND
*-----------------------------------
* Operation/tool-change header attributes. All three source POST-type
* attributes (not the risky VALUE-type category that caused nine rounds
* of trouble with Material) - same low-risk pattern as PART NAME DISP,
* which worked correctly on the first attempt.
:ATTRNAME=TOOL COMMENT DISP
:ATTRTYPE=POST
:ATTREMARK=Tool comment, bare value for custom tool-change header
:CODETYPE=FORMAT
:VAR=TOOL COMMENT
:LEFT_PLACES=0
:RIGHT_PLACES=0
:UNITFLAG=NON_CONVERT
:ATTRSPACES=YES
:ATTRUSED=1
:ATTREND
*-----------------------------------
* Unverified whether TLP_OPER_NAME matches the operation name shown in the
* CAMWorks feature tree - confirm actual displayed value once compiled.
:ATTRNAME=OPER NAME DISP
:ATTRTYPE=POST
:ATTREMARK=Operation name from SW/CAMWorks, bare value for custom header
:CODETYPE=FORMAT
:VAR=TLP_OPER_NAME
:LEFT_PLACES=0
:RIGHT_PLACES=0
:UNITFLAG=NON_CONVERT
:ATTRSPACES=YES
:ATTRUSED=1
:ATTREND
*-----------------------------------
:ATTRNAME=OPR COMMENT DISP
:ATTRTYPE=POST
:ATTREMARK=Operation comment, bare value for custom operation header
:CODETYPE=FORMAT
:VAR=OPR COMMENT
:LEFT_PLACES=0
:RIGHT_PLACES=0
:UNITFLAG=NON_CONVERT
:ATTRSPACES=YES
:ATTRUSED=1
:ATTREND
*-----------------------------------
* Tracks the last coolant state actually set. Safe now that coolant is
* ONLY ever touched in one place (CALC_OUTPUT_OPER_COMMENT) - the earlier
* version of this had a second, independent emission point (tool change),
* which let this tracker drift out of sync with what was actually last
* output, causing spurious on/off/on flicker. Removed that second point
* entirely instead of trying to keep two trackers in sync.
:ATTRNAME=PREV COOLANT
:ATTRTYPE=POST
:ATTRVTYPE=INTEGER
:ATTREMARK=Last coolant state actually set (tracks Flood/Mist/Off)
:ATTREND
*-----------------------------------
:ATTRNAME=NEW COOLANT
:ATTRTYPE=POST
:ATTRVTYPE=INTEGER
:ATTREMARK=Coolant state computed for the current operation (scratch var)
:ATTREND
*-----------------------------------
* Own operation counter, incremented in CALC_CHECK_OPER_COMMENTS -
* independent of the native OPER_COUNT variable, to avoid uncertainty
* about whether that's reliably incremented before our code runs on
* every path (tool-change vs non-tool-change operations).
:ATTRNAME=OP NUM
:ATTRTYPE=POST
:ATTRVTYPE=INTEGER
:ATTREMARK=Our own operation counter, starts at 1
:ATTREND
*-----------------------------------
:ATTRNAME=OPER NUM DISP
:ATTRTYPE=POST
:ATTRVTYPE=INTEGER
:ATTREMARK=Operation number for the header, e.g. "Operation #1"
:CODETYPE=FORMAT
:VAR=OP NUM
:LEFT_PLACES=0
:RIGHT_PLACES=0
:CANNOT_BE_DECIMAL
:CANNOT_BE_SIGNED
:UNITFLAG=NON_CONVERT
:ATTREND
*-----------------------------------
* Tracks the operation name from the previous CALC_CHECK_OPER_COMMENTS
* call, to detect and skip duplicate calls for what's actually the same
* logical operation split into multiple internal CAMWorks sub-segments.
* Confirmed via diagnostic testing that this was silently truncating
* around 26 chars without an explicit ATTRINLEN, breaking comparison for
* longer operation names like "Counter Bores For Mounting Screws" (34
* chars) - that's the real root cause of the duplicate headers.
:ATTRNAME=PREV OPER NAME
:ATTRTYPE=POST
:ATTRVTYPE=CHARACTER
:ATTRINLEN=80
:ATTREMARK=Last operation name seen, for de-duplication
:ATTREND
*-----------------------------------
* Flag set inside CALC_OUTPUT_OPER_COMMENT to detect whether
* GET_OPER_COMMENTS actually invoked it (meaning real notes existed) -
* lets CALC_CHECK_OPER_COMMENTS tell genuinely-empty notes apart from
* notes that were already handled by the native callback.
:ATTRNAME=GOT NOTES
:ATTRTYPE=POST
:ATTRVTYPE=INTEGER
:ATTREMARK=Whether GET_OPER_COMMENTS fired our callback this call
:ATTREND
*-----------------------------------
* Bare tool number for the tool-change header ("Tool #2" not "T02") - the
* existing T attribute zero-pads for the actual G-code T word, this is a
* separate, unpadded display copy.
:ATTRNAME=TOOL NUM RAW DISP
:ATTRTYPE=POST
:ATTRVTYPE=INTEGER
:ATTREMARK=Raw tool number, no zero-padding, for the tool-change header
:CODETYPE=FORMAT
:VAR=TOOL
:LEFT_PLACES=0
:RIGHT_PLACES=0
:CANNOT_BE_DECIMAL
:CANNOT_BE_SIGNED
:UNITFLAG=NON_CONVERT
:ATTREND
*-----------------------------------
* Scratch variables for the tool-table de-duplication scan.
:ATTRNAME=IS DUPLICATE
:ATTRTYPE=POST
:ATTRVTYPE=INTEGER
:ATTREMARK=Whether this array position's tool already appeared earlier
:ATTREND
*-----------------------------------
:ATTRNAME=SCAN I
:ATTRTYPE=POST
:ATTRVTYPE=INTEGER
:ATTREMARK=Loop index for the duplicate-detection scan
:ATTREND
*-----------------------------------
* Scratch variables for the quadrant-splitting CALC_RADIAL_ARCS override
* (full circles cannot be expressed in R-format; split into four
* 90-degree arcs). Unique QSPLIT prefix - no native name collisions
* (verified by search, per the CALC_PRELOAD_TOOL array-collision lesson).
:ATTRNAME=QSPLIT FLAG
:ATTRTYPE=POST
:ATTRVTYPE=INTEGER
:ATTREMARK=1 when the current arc is a full circle needing quadrant split
:ATTREND
*-----------------------------------
:ATTRNAME=QSPLIT STEP
:ATTRTYPE=POST
:ATTRVTYPE=INTEGER
:ATTREMARK=Quadrant angle step: +90 CCW, -90 CW
:ATTREND
*-----------------------------------
:ATTRNAME=QSPLIT COUNT
:ATTRTYPE=POST
:ATTRVTYPE=INTEGER
:ATTREMARK=Quadrant loop counter (1..3 intermediate points)
:ATTREND
*-----------------------------------
:ATTRNAME=QSPLIT ANG
:ATTRTYPE=POST
:ATTRVTYPE=DECIMAL
:ATTREMARK=Current quadrant point angle, degrees
:ATTREND
